      <div class="column-fixed">
        <div class="text-container-1">
          <b>Elvin Odelholm</b>
          <p>Art Director based in Stockholm.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="text-container-2" id="text-container-2">
          <p id="text-red" >
            <b>13:6 Collaborations</b><br>
            <i>Art Direction, Photography, Graphic Design</i><br><br>
            Graphic identity, running order and promotion for the Beckmans Collaboration Show 2025. 
            The fashion students wanted a classic look with a focus on raw materials. Following the theme, I shot the models against a lit softbox as a backdrop, creating stark contrast and a raw, unpolished frame that became central to the visual identity.
            <br><br>
            <b>Creative Direction:</b> Annika Berner<br>
            <b>Art Direction:</b> Elvin Odelholm<br>
            <b>Photography & Design :</b> Elvin Odelholm<br>
            <b>Head of Course:</b> Elisabet Yanagisawa<br>
            <b>Head of Programme:</b> Per Engsheden<br>
                        <b>Collaborating Brands:</b> Arket, Asket, & Other Stories, <br>Rave Review, Remake, Weekday</b>

          </p>

          <p id="text-purple"><b>Core Curriculum / Centralt Inneh√•ll</b><br>
            <i>Art Direction, Photography, Graphic Design</i><br><br>
            A photo series and a book as part of my graduation project at Beckmans College of Design. After 17 years of school, I looked back on my experience of school and realised that a big part of my memories revolved around small, seemingly pointless activities, things that had nothing to do with grades or curriculum. I wanted to highlight these memories and question what we consider meaningful or meaningless. Using a wig and some post-production, I stepped into the role of a schoolchild and restaged a series of memories. I then compiled the photos into a book inspired by the official Swedish curriculum.  
            <br><br>Awarded with a scholarship from <a href="https://happy.forsman.com/" style="text-decoration: underline;">F&amp;B Happy</a>.
            <br><br>
            <b>Art Direction, Design &amp; Photography:</b> Elvin Odelholm<br>
            <b>Head of Course:</b> Sophia Wood
          </p>

          <p id="text-green"><b>Collecting Music</b><br>
            <i>Art Direction, Graphic Design</i><br><br>
            We were assigned to create magazines about music. My group decided to use collecting and statistics as our angle. I made a centrefold poster illustrating the 100 most common nouns in the lyrics of the 100 most streamed songs. 
            <br><br>
            <b>Team:</b> Elvin Odelholm, Adam Arinbjarnarson, Solvej Jansson<br>
            <b>Head of Course:</b> Stefania Malmsten
          </p>

          <p id="text-orange"><b>Ad Space</b><br>
            <i>Concept, Photography</i><br><br>
        Part of the application process for Beckmans College of Design was to design large-scale public typography. Since Beckmans has a background as an advertising school, I proposed a new way of generating ad revenue, writing <i>Ad Space For Rent</i> on a horse, alongside my phone number. Unfortunately, I received no calls.            <br><br>
            
          </p>

          <p id="text-yellow"><b>The Little Conscience</b><br>
             <i>Art Direction</i><br><br>
              Svenskt Tenn wanted to communicate that their profits go to research. My class at Beckmans was therefore given the task of creating a scientific exhibition in their store. A friend and I teamed up and based our project on a research theme about AI as a kind of superstrong external conscience. Then we built a two-meter-tall styrofoam muscle monster sculpture of Jiminy Cricket. 
              <br><br>
              The piece was later exhibited at the Royal Swedish Academy of Sciences and at Riche Fenix in Stockholm.             <br><br>
            <b>Partner:</b> Svenskt Tenn, The Beijer Foundation<br>
            <b>Team:</b> Elvin Odelholm, Jonatan Modin<br>
            <b>Project Lead:</b> Sophia Wood
          </p>

          <p id="text-black"><b>Atelier Cru</b><br>
            <i>Art Direction, Photography</i><br><br>
            Atelier Cru launched a collection exploring how zips and folds can make garments modifiable. I art directed and hands on created a photography campaign inspired by this idea of shapeshifting silhouettes and moving beyond the natural form.
            <br><br>
            <b>Client:</b> Atelier Cru<br>
            <b>Art Director:</b> Elvin Odelholm<br>
            <b>Photography:</b> Elvin Odelholm<br>
            <b>Project Lead:</b> G√∂ran Sundberg<br>
            <b>Fashion Editor:</b> Rebecca Cohen<br>
          </p>

        <p id="text-white"><b>G√• inte in i v√§ggen-klockan</b><br>
            <i>Art Direction</i><br><br>
             <i>Art Direction</i><br><br>
  Ahead of Beckmans‚Äô annual Christmas market at Rosendals Tr√§dg√•rd, stress levels at school were high. I wanted to create a Christmas gift that reminded people to take breaks. Based on the Pomodoro technique, I designed an egg timer that lets you work in 30-minute intervals. The message luckily spread to both stressed-out industry professionals and to holiday-celebrating families.
          <br><br>
            <a href="https://www.resume.se/kommunikation/varumarke/aggklockan-fran-beckmansstudenten-ska-forhindra-mental-krasch/" target="_blank" style="text-decoration: underline;">Resum√©</a>


          <br><br>
          </p>

           <p id="text-pink"><b>Books</b><br>
            <i>Graphic Design</i><br><br>
            A selection of 50+ published covers.<br><br>
            <b>Clients:</b> Opal, Saga Egmont &amp; Berghs F√∂rlag <br>
            <br> <br>
          </p>


          <p id="text-blue"><b>Material Worlds</b><br>
            <i>Art Direction, Photography, Graphic Design</i><br><br>
            Lookbook for a Beckmans Fashion Show. To highlight the materials and the concept Material Worlds, we took close-up shots of the specific garments and turned them into postcard-like landscapes. The models were then placed within these landscapes for the images in the lookbook. In addition to the landscapes, the lookbook was inspired by the size of postcards and their handwritten notes.
            <br><br>
            <b>Art Direction:</b> Elvin Odelholm<br>
            <b>Photography:</b> Jesper Smeding<br>
            <b>Head of Course:</b> G√∂ran Sundberg<br>
            <b>Head of Programe:</b> Per Engsheden
          </p>


          <p id="text-grey" class="active"><b></b><br>
